    "summary": "Jarmo (also spelled Qal'at Jarmo) is a Neolithic site located in the foothills of the Zagros Mountains in northeastern Iraq, excavated by Robert Braidwood of the Oriental Institute, University of Chicago, during the late 1940s and 1950s. Occupied from approximately 7500 to 6500 BCE, Jarmo is one of the earliest known farming villages in Mesopotamia and the greater Near East, and its excavation played a formative role in developing the modern understanding of the Neolithic transition.\n\nAt Jarmo, Braidwood found evidence of domesticated emmer wheat, einkorn wheat, and two-row barley, alongside the bones of domesticated goats and possibly dogs and pigs — making it one of the earliest sites to document the full agricultural package in a highland Mesopotamian context. The settlement consisted of small rectangular mud-brick and mud-walled houses, and the inhabitants produced a range of stone tools including ground stone grinding equipment for processing grain. Early phases of occupation lacked pottery, while later levels contained simple handmade clay vessels, providing evidence for the introduction of ceramics into this community during its occupation history.\n\nJarmo's significance lies in its demonstration that farming villages existed in the foothills zone of the Zagros well before such communities appeared in the Mesopotamian lowlands. The highland zone provided wild progenitors of domesticated plants and animals, suggesting that the agricultural transition may have begun in the piedmont zone before spreading into the river valleys. The site remains a landmark in the archaeological study of the origins of agriculture.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jarmo",
